# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christianisation-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The **Abbey of Kells** (Irish: *Mainistir Cheanannais*) or **Kells Priory** is a former monastery in Kells, County Meath, Ireland, 59 kilometres (37 mi) north-west of Dublin.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] It was founded in the early 9th century, and the Book of Kells was kept there during the later medieval and early modern periods before finally leaving the abbey in the 1650s.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Much of the Book of Kells may have been created there, but historians cannot be certain of the exact date and circumstances of its creation.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The Abbey of Kells was reportedly founded by St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] 554, after High King Diarmuid Mac Caroll of Tara granted the land.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The Abbey was refounded from Iona, the building taking from 807 until the consecration of the church in 814.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] In 814, Cellach, Abbot of Iona, retired to Kells, but, contrary to what is sometimes claimed, it is clear from the *Annals* that Iona remained the main Columban house for several decades, despite the danger of Viking raids.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Only in 878 were the main relics, with Columba's reliquary shrine specified in the records, moved to Ireland, with Kells becoming the new main Columban house.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Though not mentioned, this might well have been when the Book of Kells came to Kells.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Among other theories, it is believed that the Book of Kells may have been either started in Iona and finished in Kells or written entirely in the scriptorium at Kells by successive generations of monks.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The Vikings continually raided the abbey during the 10th century and it was repeatedly sacked and pillaged.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Despite the constant raids, the monks managed to keep the Book of Kells intact until 1006 when it was stolen from the shrine.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] A reference in the *Annals of Ulster* is generally believed to refer the theft of the Book of Kells and it relates that the manuscript was returned after two months without its cover.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The force of the removal of the cover probably explains the missing illustrations at the beginning and end of the book.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The book was stored in the abbey for the remainder of the Middle Ages.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] In the 12th century, details of land charters for the abbey were copied onto blank pages of the Book of Kells as was common practice for the period.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] This is the earliest confirmed reference to its presence at the abbey.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Later in the same century, the monastery was dissolved with the abbey becoming a parish church and the Book of Kells continued to be kept there.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The Book of Kells remained at Kells until the 1650s when Oliver Cromwell's troops were stationed in the town.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] At that point it was sent to Dublin for safekeeping.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] In 1661, the Book of Kells was acquired by Trinity College Dublin where it remains.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Today, the monastic site includes a 10th-century round tower that rises around 28 metres (92 ft) from the original street level.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] It has five windows on the top floor rather than the usual four, overlooking the five roads leading into Kells.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The current church building (Church of Ireland) dates to 1778 and was renovated in 1965.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] There are also a number of 9th- to 10th-century high crosses.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Three crosses and a cross base are located on the site itself, whilst the 9th-century "Market Cross" (originally at the abbey's eastern gate) is now located in front of the old courthouse.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] Legend has it that it was damaged by Cromwellian soldiers and that it was used to hang participants of the 1798 rebellion.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbey-of-kells] The round tower and high crosses are a National Monument of Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The title had its origin in the monasteries of Egypt and Syria, spread through the eastern Mediterranean, and soon became accepted generally in all languages as the designation of the head of a monastery.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The word is derived from the Aramaic **av** meaning "father" or **abba**, meaning "my father" (it still has this meaning in contemporary Arabic: أب, Hebrew: אבא and Aramaic: ܐܒܐ) In the Septuagint, it was written as "abbas".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] At first it was employed as a respectful title for any monk, but it was soon restricted by canon law to certain priestly superiors.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] At times it was applied to various priests, e.g. at the court of the Frankish monarchy the **Abbas palatinus** ("of the palace"') and **Abbas castrensis** ("of the camp") were chaplains to the Merovingian and Carolingian sovereigns' court and army respectively.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The title of abbot came into fairly general use in western monastic orders whose members include priests.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The English version for a female monastic head is abbess.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In Egypt, the first home of monasticism, the jurisdiction of the abbot, or archimandrite, was but loosely defined.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Sometimes he ruled over only one community, sometimes over several, each of which had its own abbot as well.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Saint John Cassian speaks of an abbot of the Thebaid who had 500 monks under him.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] By the Rule of St Benedict, which, until the Cluniac reforms, was the norm in the West, the abbot has jurisdiction over only one community.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The rule, as was inevitable, was subject to frequent violations; but it was not until the foundation of the Cluniac Order that the idea of a supreme abbot, exercising jurisdiction over all the houses of an order, was definitely recognised.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Monks, as a rule, were laymen, nor at the outset was the abbot any exception.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] For the reception of the sacraments, and for other religious offices, the abbot and his monks were commanded to attend the nearest church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] This rule proved inconvenient when a monastery was situated in a desert or at a distance from a city, and necessity compelled the ordination of some monks.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] This innovation was not introduced without a struggle, ecclesiastical dignity being regarded as inconsistent with the higher spiritual life, but, before the close of the 5th century, at least in the East, abbots seem almost universally to have become deacons, if not priests.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The change spread more slowly in the West, where the office of abbot was commonly filled by laymen till the end of the 7th century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The ecclesiastical leadership exercised by abbots despite their frequent lay status is proved by their attendance and votes at ecclesiastical councils.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Thus at the first Council of Constantinople, AD 448, 23 archimandrites or abbots sign, with 30 bishops.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The second Council of Nicaea, AD 787, recognized the right of abbots to ordain their monks to the inferior orders below the diaconate, a power usually reserved to bishops.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Abbots used to be subject to episcopal jurisdiction, and continued generally so, in fact, in the West till the 11th century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The Code of Justinian (lib. i. tit. iii. de Ep. leg. xl.) expressly subordinates the abbot to episcopal oversight.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] These exceptions, introduced with a good object, had grown into a widespread evil by the 12th century, virtually creating an *imperium in imperio,* and depriving the bishop of all authority over the chief centres of influence in his diocese.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the 12th century, the abbots of Fulda claimed precedence of the archbishop of Cologne.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Abbots more and more assumed almost episcopal state, and in defiance of the prohibition of early councils and the protests of St Bernard and others, adopted the episcopal insignia of mitre, ring, gloves and sandals.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] It has been maintained that the right to wear mitres was sometimes granted by the popes to abbots before the 11th century, but the documents on which this claim is based are not genuine (J.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The first undoubted instance is the bull by which Alexander II in 1063 granted the use of the mitre to Egelsinus, abbot of the monastery of St Augustine at Canterbury.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Of these the precedence was yielded to the abbot of Glastonbury, until in AD 1154 Adrian IV (Nicholas Breakspear) granted it to the abbot of St Alban's, in which monastery he had been brought up.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Next after the abbot of St Alban's ranked the abbot of Westminster and then Ramsey.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Elsewhere, the mitred abbots that sat in the Estates of Scotland were of Arbroath, Cambuskenneth, Coupar Angus, Dunfermline, Holyrood, Iona, Kelso, Kilwinning, Kinloss, Lindores, Paisley, Melrose, Scone, St Andrews Priory and Sweetheart.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The adoption of certain episcopal insignia (pontificalia) by abbots was followed by an encroachment on episcopal functions, which had to be specially but ineffectually guarded against by the Lateran council, AD 1123.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Of course, they always and everywhere had the power of admitting their own monks and vesting them with the religious habit.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The power of the abbot was paternal but absolute, limited, however, by the canon law.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] One of the main goals of monasticism was the purgation of self and selfishness, and obedience was seen as a path to that perfection.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] It was sacred duty to execute the abbot's orders, and even to act without his orders was sometimes considered a transgression.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] When a vacancy occurred, the bishop of the diocese chose the abbot out of the monks of the monastery, but the right of election was transferred by jurisdiction to the monks themselves, reserving to the bishop the confirmation of the election and the benediction of the new abbot.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In abbeys exempt from the archbishop's diocesan jurisdiction, the confirmation and benediction had to be conferred by the pope in person, the house being taxed with the expenses of the new abbot's journey to Rome.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In some exceptional cases an abbot was allowed to name his own successor.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Cassian speaks of an abbot in Egypt doing this; and in later times we have another example in the case of St Bruno.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Popes and sovereigns gradually encroached on the rights of the monks, until in Italy the pope had usurped the nomination of all abbots, and the king in France, with the exception of Cluny, Premontré and other houses, chiefs of their order.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The election was for life, unless the abbot was canonically deprived by the chiefs of his order, or when he was directly subject to them, by the pope or the bishop, and also in England it was for a term of 8–12 years.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The ceremony of the formal admission of a Benedictine abbot in medieval times is thus prescribed by the consuetudinary of Abingdon.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The newly elected abbot was to put off his shoes at the door of the church, and proceed barefoot to meet the members of the house advancing in a procession.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] After proceeding up the nave, he was to kneel and pray at the topmost step of the entrance of the choir, into which he was to be introduced by the bishop or his commissary, and placed in his stall.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The monks, then kneeling, gave him the kiss of peace on the hand, and rising, on the mouth, the abbot holding his staff of office.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] He then put on his shoes in the vestry, and a chapter was held, and the bishop or his delegate preached a suitable sermon.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Before the late modern era, the abbot was treated with the utmost reverence by the brethren of his house.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] When he appeared either in church or chapter all present rose and bowed.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] His letters were received kneeling, as were those of the pope and the king.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] No monk might sit in his presence, or leave it, without his permission, reflecting the hierarchical etiquette of families and society.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The highest place was assigned to him, both in church and at table.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the East he was commanded to eat with the other monks.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the West, the Rule of St Benedict appointed him a separate table, at which he might entertain guests and strangers.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Because this permission opened the door to luxurious living, Synods of Aachen decreed that the abbot should dine in the refectory, and be content with the ordinary fare of the monks, unless he had to entertain a guest.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] These ordinances proved, however, generally ineffective to secure strictness of diet, and contemporaneous literature abounds with satirical remarks and complaints concerning the inordinate extravagance of the tables of the abbots.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] When the abbot condescended to dine in the refectory, his chaplains waited upon him with the dishes, a servant, if necessary, assisting them.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] When abbots dined in their own private hall, the Rule of St Benedict charged them to invite their monks to their table, provided there was room, on which occasions the guests were to abstain from quarrels, slanderous talk and idle gossiping.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The ordinary attire of the abbot was according to rule to be the same as that of the monks.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] But by the 10th century the rule was commonly set aside, and we find frequent complaints of abbots dressing in silk, and adopting sumptuous attire.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Some even laid aside the monastic habit altogether, and assumed a secular dress.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] With the increase of wealth and power, abbots had lost much of their special religious character, and become great lords, chiefly distinguished from lay lords by celibacy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Thus we hear of abbots going out to hunt, with their men carrying bows and arrows; keeping horses, dogs and huntsmen; and special mention is made of an abbot of Leicester, c.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] 1360, who was the most skilled of all the nobility in hare hunting.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In magnificence of equipage and retinue the abbots vied with the first nobles of the realm.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] They rode on mules with gilded bridles, rich saddles and housings, carrying hawks on their wrist, followed by an immense train of attendants.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The bells of the churches were rung as they passed.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] They associated on equal terms with laymen of the highest distinction, and shared all their pleasures and pursuits.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] This rank and power was, however, often used most beneficially.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] His table, attendance and officers were an honour to the nation.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] He would entertain as many as 500 persons of rank at one time, besides relieving the poor of the vicinity twice a week.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] He had his country houses and fisheries, and when he travelled to attend parliament his retinue amounted to upwards of 100 persons.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The abbots of Cluny and Vendôme were, by virtue of their office, cardinals of the Roman church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Thus the chief magistrate of the republic at Genoa was called **Abbas Populi**.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] **defensores**, **abbacomites**, **abbates laici**, **abbates milites**, **abbates saeculares** or **irreligiosi**, **abbatiarii**, or sometimes simply **abbates**) were the outcome of the growth of the feudal system from the 8th century onwards.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] During the Carolingian epoch, the custom grew up of granting these as regular heritable fiefs or benefices, and by the 10th century, before the great Cluniac reform, the system was firmly established.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Even the abbey of St Denis was held in commendam by Hugh Capet.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The example of the kings was followed by the feudal nobles, sometimes by making a temporary concession permanent, sometimes without any form of commendation whatever.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In England the abuse was rife in the 8th century, as may be gathered from the acts of the council of Cloveshoe.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] These lay abbacies were not merely a question of overlordship, but implied the concentration in lay hands of all the rights, immunities and jurisdiction of the foundations, i.e. the more or less complete secularization of spiritual institutions.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The lay abbot took his recognized rank in the feudal hierarchy, and was free to dispose of his fief as in the case of any other.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The enfeoffment of abbeys differed in form and degree.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Sometimes the monks were directly subject to the lay abbot; sometimes he appointed a substitute to perform the spiritual functions, known usually as dean (*decanus*), but also as abbot (**abbas legitimus**, **monasticus**, **regularis**).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] When the great reform of the 11th century had put an end to the direct jurisdiction of the lay abbots, the honorary title of abbot continued to be held by certain of the great feudal families, as late as the 13th century and later, with the head of the community retaining the title of dean.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The connection of the lesser lay abbots with the abbeys, especially in the south of France, lasted longer; and certain feudal families retained the title of *abbés chevaliers* (Latin: *abbates milites*) for centuries, together with certain rights over the abbey lands or revenues.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] John, patriarch of Antioch at the beginning of the 12th century, informs us that in his time most monasteries had been handed over to laymen, **beneficiarii**, for life, or for part of their lives, by the emperors.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In conventual cathedrals, where the bishop occupied the place of the abbot, the functions usually devolving on the superior of the monastery were performed by a prior.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the Roman Catholic Church and Evangelical-Lutheran Churches, abbots continue to be elected by the monks of an abbey to lead them as their religious superior in those orders and monasteries that make use of the term (some orders of monks, as the Carthusians for instance, have only priors).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Prior to this, the monastery would be a mere priory, headed by a prior who acts as superior but without the same degree of legal authority that an abbot has.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The abbot is chosen by the monks from among the fully professed monks.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Once chosen, he must request blessing: the blessing of an abbot is celebrated by the bishop in whose diocese the monastery is or, with his permission, another abbot or bishop.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The ceremony of such a blessing is similar in some aspects to the consecration of a bishop, with the new abbot being presented with the mitre, the ring, and the crosier as symbols of office and receiving the laying on of hands and blessing from the celebrant.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Though the ceremony installs the new abbot into a position of legal authority, it does not confer further sacramental authority- it is not a further degree of Holy Orders (although some abbots have been ordained to the episcopacy).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The abbey is a species of "exempt religious" in that it is, for the most part, answerable to the pope, or to the abbot primate, rather than to the local bishop.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The abbot wears the same habit as his fellow monks, though by tradition he adds to it a pectoral cross.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Territorial abbots follow all of the above, but in addition must receive a mandate of authority from the pope over the territory around the monastery for which they are responsible.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In some monastic families, there is a hierarchy of precedence or authority among abbots.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In some cases, this is the result of an abbey being considered the "mother" of several "daughter" abbeys founded as dependent priories of the "mother".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In other cases, abbeys have affiliated in networks known as "congregations".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Some monastic families recognize one abbey as the motherhouse of the entire order.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] *abate*), as commonly used in the Catholic Church on the European continent, is the equivalent of the English "Father" (parallel etymology), being loosely applied to all who have received the tonsure.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] This use of the title is said to have originated in the right conceded to the king of France, by the concordat between Pope Leo X and Francis I (1516), to appoint commendatory abbots (**abbés commendataires**) to most of the abbeys in France.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The expectation of obtaining these sinecures drew young men towards the church in considerable numbers, and the class of abbés so formed – **abbés de cour** they were sometimes called, and sometimes (ironically) **abbés de sainte espérance** ("abbés of holy hope; or in a jeu de mots, "of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Hope") – came to hold a recognized position.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The connection many of them had with the church was of the slenderest kind, consisting mainly in adopting the title of abbé, after a remarkably moderate course of theological study, practising celibacy and wearing distinctive dress, a short dark-violet coat with narrow collar.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Being men of presumed learning and undoubted leisure, many of the class found admission to the houses of the French nobility as tutors or advisers.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The class did not survive the Revolution; but the courtesy title of abbé, having long lost all connection in people's minds with any special ecclesiastical function, remained as a convenient general term applicable to any clergyman.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the Eastern Orthodox and Eastern Catholic Churches, the abbot is referred to as the *hegumen*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The Superior of a monastery of nuns is called the *Hēguménē*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The title of *archimandrite* (literally the head of the enclosure) used to mean something similar.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the East, the principle set forth in the *Corpus Juris Civilis* still applies, whereby most abbots are immediately subject to the local bishop.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Those monasteries which enjoy the status of being *stauropegic* will be subject only to a primate or his Synod of Bishops and not the local bishop.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the Eastern Orthodox Church, only monastics are permitted to be elevated to the rank of archimandrite.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Married priests are elevated to the parallel rank of Archpriest or Protopresbyter.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Normally there are no celibate priests who are not monastics in the Orthodox Church, with the exception of married priests who have been widowed.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Since the time of Catherine II the ranks of Abbot and Archimandrite have been given as honorary titles in the Russian Church, and may be given to any monastic, even if he does not in fact serve as the superior of a monastery.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In Greek practice the title or function of Abbot corresponds to a person who serves as the head of a monastery, although the title of the Archimandrite may be given to any celibate priest who could serve as the head of a monastery.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the German Evangelical Church, the German title of *Abt* (abbot) is sometimes bestowed, like the French *abbé*, as an honorary distinction, and additionally designates the heads of monasteries, with a number of these that accepted the Evangelical-Lutheran faith at the time of the Reformation.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Of these the most noteworthy is Loccum Abbey in Hanover, founded as a Cistercian house in 1163 by Count Wilbrand of Hallermund, and Lutheranised in 1593.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The abbot of Loccum, who still carries a pastoral staff, takes precedence over all the clergy of Hanover, and was *ex officio* a member of the consistory of the kingdom.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The governing body of the abbey consists of the abbot, prior and the "convent", or community, of *Stiftsherren* (canons).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] With respect to Anglicanism, in the Church of England, the Bishop of Norwich, by royal decree given by Henry VIII, also holds the honorary title of "Abbot of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Benet." This title hails back to England's separation from the See of Rome, when King Henry, as supreme head of the newly independent church, took over all of the monasteries, mainly for their possessions, except for St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Benet, which he spared because the abbot and his monks possessed no wealth, and lived like simple beggars, deposing the incumbent Bishop of Norwich and seating the abbot in his place, thus the dual title still held to this day.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Additionally, at the enthronement of the Archbishop of Canterbury, there is a threefold enthronement, once in the throne the chancel as the diocesan bishop of Canterbury, once in the Chair of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Augustine as the Primate of All England, and then once in the chapter-house as Titular Abbot of Canterbury.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] There are several Benedictine abbeys throughout the Anglican Communion.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] "The Abbot" is one of the archetypes traditionally illustrated in scenes of *Danse Macabre*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] The lives of numerous abbots make up a significant contribution to Christian hagiography, one of the most well-known being the *Life of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] During the years 1106–1107 AD, Daniel, a Russian Orthodox abbot, made a pilgrimage to the Holy Land and recorded his experiences.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] His diary was much-read throughout Russia, and at least seventy-five manuscript copies survive.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] Saint Joseph, Abbot of Volokolamsk, Russia (1439–1515), wrote a number of influential works against heresy, and about monastic and liturgical discipline, and Christian philanthropy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] In the *Tales of Redwall* series, the creatures of Redwall are led by an abbot or abbess.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] These "abbots" are appointed by the brothers and sisters of Redwall to serve as a superior and provide paternal care, much like real abbots.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abbot] "The Abbot" was a nickname of RZA from the Wu-Tang Clan.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Etymologically, *Abercorn* is a Cumbric place-name.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It is recorded as *Aebbercurnig* in c.731.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The first element is *aber* 'mouth, confluence'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Watson proposed that the second element meant 'horned', from a Brittonic word related to Welsh *corniog*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The name would thus mean 'horned confluence'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] However, because Abercorn sits by the Cornie Burn, Alan James has suggested that the name means 'mouth of the Cornie Burn'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The name of the stream itself is also Cumbric and seems to derive from **kernan* 'mound, hill' and so to be named after the hill on which Abercorn stands.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The English monk and historian Bede mentions Abercorn as the site of a monastery and seat of Bishop Trumwine, who was the only bishop of the Northumbrian see of the Picts.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The 7th-century monastery is now known to have existed close to the present-day church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The church itself dates partially from the 12th century, although its most interesting features are the private aisles created for the three major families of the area, the Dalyells, the Hamiltons, and later the Hopes, who had their own enclosure behind the altar built by architect William Bruce.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The Hope mausoleum, designed by William Burn, is located adjacent to the kirkyard.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Older burial monuments include Norse "hogback" grave markers, and fragments of 7th-century Northumbrian crosses.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Adjacent to the churchyard at Abercorn, is a small museum containing prominent examples of medieval gravestones.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The lands of Abercorn were granted to Claud Hamilton in the 16th century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] His son was later created the Earl of Abercorn.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] In the early 17th century, a branch of the Hamilton dynasty moved to Ulster in Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The family would, henceforth, play a major part in Ulster affairs.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Thus, the estate was later sold to the Hope family, who were created Earls of Hopetoun, and built Hopetoun House to the east of the village.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] On the approach to the church, the Factor's house is a prominent L-shaped building in the Scottish baronial style, built circa 1855.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The House of the Binns, seat of the Dalyell family, is within the parish.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Abercorn's population was recorded as 1,044 at the time of the 1821 census, although it has since declined.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] A castle also existed here, near Hope Burn, from the 12th century, belonging to the Avenel family.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It passed through marriage to the Graham family in the mid-13th century and to the Mure family in the early 14th century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The Clan Douglas acquired the castle in about 1400.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It was besieged and sacked in 1455 by James II in his attack against the "Black Douglases" and their chief James Douglas, 9th Earl of Douglas.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It passed to the Seton family but they did not restore the castle and it was thereafter left to decay, such that it is now only marked by an earth mound.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The site was excavated by archaeologists in 1963.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] For a very short time, Abercorn was a residential bishopric.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] In 681, during the reign of King Ecgfrith of Northumbria, Theodore of Tarsus, Archbishop of Canterbury, appointed Trumwine "Bishop of the Picts", with his seat at Abercorn.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] This was part of a more general division of the Northumbrian church by Theodore, who also created the Bishopric of Hexham by separation from the Bishopric of Lindisfarne.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] Four years later, Trumwine may have been present at the defeat and death of Ecgfrith at the Battle of Dun Nechtain, after which he was forced to flee from his Pictish bishopric, retiring to the monastery at Whitby.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The bishopric of Abercorn thus ceased to be a residential diocese.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It is today listed by the Catholic Church as a titular see.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] The diocese was nominally restored as a Latin Catholic titular bishopric in 1973.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abercorn] It must not be confounded with the former Diocese of Abercorn in southern Africa.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] The parish of Aberlemno had a population of 544 at the 2011 Census.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] A genus of fossil plants first found in a nearby quarry is named *Aberlemnia* in honour of the location.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] A notable Scottish-American poet, engineer, and editor, James Mackintosh Kennedy, was born in Aberlemno in 1848, and developed his interest in literature through books lent to him by the Aberlemno church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] The Parish was the location of a Royal Observer Corps monitoring bunker between 1961 and 1968.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] It remains mostly intact and as of 2015, it was being restored.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/aberlemno] Aberlemno is notable for the presence of four early Medieval standing stones, as well as a fifth that is currently on display at McManus Galleries in Dundee.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Formerly the site of a number of Roman encampments, Abernethy became an important Pictish religious and political centre.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village was the setting for the Treaty of Abernethy, where Malcolm Canmore gave allegiance to William the Conqueror and its mediaeval round tower marks the site of a former abbey and, later, collegiate church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The civil parish of Abernethy also contains the nearby settlement of Aberargie and traditionally extends to Mugdrum Island in the Firth of Tay.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy, recorded in the 10th century as *Aburnethige*, means 'mouth of the river Nethy'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The river-name Nethy is from the Celtic root *nect*- 'pure, clean'.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Nethy Burn flows down from the Ochil Hills past the present village.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Gaelic form of the name is *Obar Neithich*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Near to Abernethy lies the small settlement of Catochil, whose name is first attested in a sixteenth-century copy of a text from 1295, as *Cathehill*, and again in 1508 as *Catoichill*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] This place-name too is thought to be from Pictish, or its close relative Common Brittonic, from the elements **ced* ("woodland") and **ogel* ("high", its form influenced by the name of the Ochil Hills among which it lies).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] There is evidence of early settlement in the area, with a Bronze Age log boat being discovered at Carpow in 2001, believed to date from around 1,000 BC.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Carpow boat is one of the best-preserved examples in Britain, and the second-oldest example of a boat recovered in Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Remains of suspected pre-historic stone circles have been discovered to the north and south of the village.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Castle Law was the site of an Iron Age hillfort, first excavated in the late 19th century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] A group of Roman sites within the village have been given the name "the Abernethy complex", including later use of the fortress at Castle Law and the site of the former Carpow Roman Fort to the east of the village.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village was once the "capital" (or at least a major religious and political centre) of the kingdom of the Picts.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The parish church, which sits on land given by Nechtan,a king of the Picts, is dedicated to Saint Brigid of Kildare (fl.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] 451–525), and the church is said to have been founded by Dairlugdach, second abbess of Kildare, one of early Christian Ireland's major monasteries.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Several pieces of Pictish or early medieval sculpture have been found in Abernethy, including an incomplete Pictish symbol stone attached to the base of the round tower.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The location "Afarnach's Hall" referred to in the earliest mediaeval Arthurian literature is usually identified as Abernethy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy is believed to have been the seat of an early Pictish bishopric, its diocese extending westward along Strathearn.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In the 12th century the bishop's seat was moved to Muthill, then Dunblane, so that Abernethy, no longer being a residential bishopric is today listed by the Catholic Church as a titular see.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 1072, Abernethy was the site of the Treaty of Abernethy concluded between William the Conqueror and Malcolm III of Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy remained the site of a small priory of Augustinian canons, founded 1272.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In the 15th century, this priory was suppressed in favour of a collegiate church under the patronage of the Douglas Earls of Angus.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Remains of the collegiate church survived until 1802 within the present village graveyard, when they were replaced by the present plain red sandstone church, which is still dedicated to Saint Brigid.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy was granted a charter as a burgh of barony in 1476 by the 5th Earl of Angus, a status confirmed in 1628 by the 11th Earl.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Earl of Angus and Lord Abernethy have become subsidiary titles of the Dukes of Hamilton.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] It later became a police burgh and held its burgh status and instruments of local government until the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 1933, Powrie Park was gifted to the burgh by William Powrie as a memorial and is maintained as common good land by Perth and Kinross Council.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In October 1909, future Prime Minister Winston Churchill spoke at a political rally in the village, which was protested by a group of Suffragettes including Adela Pankhurst.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In the Second World War, the village hosted a camp for Polish forces and was the destination for a number of evacuees.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 2012, the London Olympics torch relay passed through Abernethy as part of its progress around the British Isles.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy was formerly associated with agriculture, including soft fruit production, salmon fishing and weaving.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] A general store is found in the village's Main Street.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The local post office was replaced in 2009 with a mobile service.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village also hosts a public house, museum, garden centre, public park and heritage gardens.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] A Gala / Fete Day is held annually on the first or second Saturday in June, with a race to the top of nearby Castle Law taking place the following day.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Museum of Abernethy in the village opened in May 2000 by Magnus Magnusson, former chairman of the Ancient Monuments Board for Scotland, and is open to the public during May to September each year.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 2025, the museum celebrated its 25th anniversary with a number of events.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy has an ancient history back to the earliest days of Christianity in Scotland, and a pivotal role in shaping it, albeit in a gently far-reaching way.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The Culdees (from the Irish Céilí Dé, meaning "Spouses of God") were ascetic Christian monks and hermits who lived in Ireland, Scotland, and Wales during the Middle Ages.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Prior to The Reformation, the village fell within the diocese of Dunblane, part of the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] As Scotland moved from Catholicism to Protestantism, the Scottish Episcopal Church was established, with the village continuing as part of a Protestant diocese of Dunblane.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The modern Scottish Episcopal Church diocese has changed and extended, becoming The Diocese of St Andrews, Dunkeld and Dunblane, part of the worldwide Anglican communion.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village falls within the Church of Scotland's ecclesiastical parish of Abernethy, Dron and Arngask.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village's parish church is known as the Kirk of St Bride and dates to the 19th century, built on the site of a former mediaeval church and monastery.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The church contains a number of stained glass windows, including two by the artist William Wilson.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The former South United Free church building, constructed in 1866, has been deconsecrated and is now in private ownership.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The former Abernethy Free church, later the North United Free church, was converted for use into a factory and demolished in the 1990s.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy Community Council matriculated a coat of arms with the Lord Lyon in 1991.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy is twinned with Grisy-Suisnes in the Île-de-France.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The historic core of Abernethy is designated as a conservation area with protections against development.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] A number of listed buildings are also designated within the village and the wider parish.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village has one of Scotland's two surviving Irish-style round towers (the other is at Brechin, Angus); both are in the care of Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The tower stands 74 ft (23 m) high, and it is possible to climb to the top, using a modern metal spiral staircase (the tower originally had several wooden floors linked by ladders).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The tower was evidently built in two stages (shown by a change in the masonry), and probably dates from the 11th to early 12th centuries.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village's war memorial is modelled on a former market cross and was unveiled in the village's square in 1921.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] It records the names of 30 men from Abernethy who died in the First World War and the names of a further eight who died in the Second World War were added later.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The 15th century Balvaird Castle, a mediaeval tower house, is located outside of the village.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy and its surrounding district are represented by Abernethy community council.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The local authority is Perth and Kinross Council with Abernethy falling within the Almond and Earn ward, one of twelve in the council area.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] For elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom, Abernethy is part of the Perth and Kinross-shire constituency in the House of Commons.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] For elections to the devolved Scottish Parliament, it is part of the Perthshire South and Kinross-shire constituency and the Mid Scotland and Fife region.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The main settlement of Abernethy was created as a burgh since 1476, while a wider parish included neighbouring small settlements such as Aberargie and had local government functions until 1930.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The parish partly extended from Perthshire into neighbouring Fife until boundary changes.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The burgh was held initially as a burgh of barony under the Earl of Angus who held the title of Lord Abernethy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Both titles are now held by the Dukes of Hamilton.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Under this system, baronial courts dealt with local issues and administered justice.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 1877, the burgh became a police burgh, with local administration carried out by Commissioners of Police.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] These were replaced by Abernethy Town Council in 1901 with its status evolving into a small burgh.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The town council, headed by a provost, continued to provide local government until its abolition in 1975 under wide-ranging local government reforms.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Its powers were taken on by the Tayside Regional Council and Perth and Kinross District Council.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 1996, a unitary authority, Perth and Kinross Council was created.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village is located near the M90 motorway, sitting on the A913 road, connecting to Cupar to the east and onward through the A912 to Perth in the west.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy railway station served the village until 1955, when it was closed by the British Transport Commission.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The line continues to operate as a branch of the Edinburgh–Dundee line, running between Perth and Ladybank.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] A campaign exists to re-open the neighbouring village of Newburgh's railway station.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] The village maintains a single non-denominational state primary school.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] Abernethy Primary School's current building was constructed in 2002 and expanded in 2013.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/abernethy-perth-and-kinross] In 2023, the school roll was 148 pupils.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was the successor to the former Scottish Council of Churches.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was one of the four national ecumenical bodies in the UK, with equivalent bodies being Churches Together in England, Cytûn in Wales and the Irish Council of Churches, plus Churches Together in Britain and Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS office was originally located in Dunblane, then in Alloa and finally in Stirling.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2019, the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland announced that ACTS would be succeeded by a new body to be called the Scottish Christian Forum.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2021 it was decided not to establish the SCF as a charity.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2024 the Scottish Christian Forum was recognised by Scottish churches as the main ecumenical organisation for Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It is an umbrella term for the Ecumenical Officers Forum and the Scottish Church Leaders' Forum.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS continues in existence as a charity, its principle activity being to provide grant aid to new local or national ecumenical initiatives in Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] From May 2018, the interim general secretary was the Rev.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Ian Boa (who succeeded the Reverend Matthew Ross, a minister of the Church of Scotland, who took up a new post with the World Council of Churches).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The assistant general secretary (since 2011) was the Reverend Ian Boa of the United Free Church of Scotland; he succeeded the Revd Lindsey Sanderson of the United Reformed Church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were also two programme officers to support the work of ACTS.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] When first created, the office of ACTS was located at the former *Scottish Churches House* in Dunblane.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2006 the ACTS office was moved to Forrester Lodge, adjacent to Inglewood House in Alloa, but in October 2015 it was relocated to Stirling, in a self-contained office within the headquarters building of *Volunteer Scotland*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Scottish Churches House was opened in 1960, closed in 2011 and subsequently converted into a hotel.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was a place for churches to meet, experience, reflect, share and act together.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were a number of projects which ACTS coordinates across Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was not intended that ACTS should develop into a "superchurch".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Prior to 2003, four member churches of ACTS were part of the "Scottish Churches Initiative for Union" (which sought institutional unity - a project which ACTS was not part of), but a negative vote at the General Assembly in 2003 necessitated the withdrawal of the Church of Scotland from SCIFU.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Henceforth, greater emphasis has been placed on the development of Local Ecumenical Partnerships.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The principle of being Churches Together was of central importance to the work of ACTS.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The agenda of ACTS was set at a national level by the church denominations through their representatives on the "Members' Meeting".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] To comply with the requirements of the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator, the legal responsibility for the oversight and governance of ACTS is vested in trustees, chaired by the convener of ACTS and supported by the Secretariat.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] As of 2025 the board of trustees remains in existence.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS worked through its Programme Groups, Partner Group and Bodies in Association.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Programme Groups (directly under the responsibility of ACTS) include the Scottish Churches Rural Group, Scottish Churches Anti-Human Trafficking Group and the Scottish Churches Education Group.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Partner Groups (administratively and financially supported by ACTS, but with autonomous management) include the Scottish Churches Racial Justice Group.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS Ecumenical Development Group promoted local ecumenism.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Before restructuring in the early 2010s, ACTS had four "Networks".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] A separate body, the Scottish Churches' Committee, is responsible for liaison with public authorities on legal (rather than spiritual) matters - such as changes to legislation and the resulting effect on churches (such as planning law, changes to local government taxation, etc.).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Seven of the nine members of ACTS are also members of the SCC (i.e. all but the two smallest, namely the Congregational Federation and the Quakers).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The SCC also includes the Baptist Church, the Free Church of Scotland and several smaller Presbyterian churches.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The Secretary of the SCC is the Solicitor of the Church of Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It also co-operates with the UK-wide Churches Legislation Advisory Services (CLAS), formerly known as the Churches' Main Committee.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán promulgated the Law of Adomnán or "Law of Innocents" (Latin: *Lex Innocentium*).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] He also wrote the treatise *De Locis Sanctis* ('On Holy Places'), an account of the great Christian holy places and centres of pilgrimage.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán got much of his information from a Frankish bishop called Arculf, who had personally visited Egypt, Rome, Constantinople and the Holy Land, and visited Iona afterwards.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán was born about 624, a relative on his father's side of Columba.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] He was a member of the Northern Uí Néill lineage Cenél Conaill.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] He was the son of Rónán mac Tinne by Ronat, a woman from another Northern Uí Néill lineage known as the Cenél nÉnda.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán's birthplace was probably in or near Raphoe, a town in what later became Tír Chonaill (now mainly County Donegal), in Ulster in the north of Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Some of Adomnán's childhood anecdotes seem to confirm at least an upbringing in this fertile eastern part of present-day County Donegal, not far from the modern city of Derry.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It is thought that Adomnán may have begun his monastic career at a Columban monastery called Druim Tuamma, but any Columban foundation in northern Ireland or Dál Riata is a possibility, although Durrow is a stronger possibility than most.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] He probably joined the Columban *familia* (i.e. the federation of monasteries under the leadership of Iona Abbey) around 640.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Some modern commentators believe that he could not have come to Iona until sometime after 669, the year of the accession of Fáilbe mac Pípáin, the first abbot of whom Adomnán gives any information.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] However, Richard Sharpe argues that he probably came to Iona during the abbacy of Ségéne (d.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Whenever or wherever Adomnán received his education, Adomnán attained a level of learning rare in early-medieval Northern Europe.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It has been suggested by Alfred Smyth that Adomnán spent some years teaching and studying at Durrow, and while this is not accepted by all scholars, it remains a strong possibility.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] In 679, Adomnán became the ninth abbot of Iona after Columba.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Abbot Adomnán enjoyed a friendship with King Aldfrith of Northumbria.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] In 684, Aldfrith stayed with Adomnán in Iona.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán, in keeping with Ionan tradition, made several more trips to the lands of the English during his abbacy, including one the following year.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It is sometimes thought, after the account given by Bede, that it was during his visits to Northumbria, under the influence of Abbot Ceolfrith, that Adomnán decided to adopt the Roman dating of Easter that had been agreed some years before at the Synod of Whitby.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Bede implies that this led to a schism at Iona, whereby Adomnán became alienated from the Iona brethren and went to Ireland to convince the Irish of the Roman dating.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Jeffrey Wetherill sees Adomnán's long absences from Iona as having led to something of an undermining of his authority; he was thus unable to persuade the monks to adopt the Roman dating of Easter, let alone the tonsure.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It is clear that Adomnán did adopt that Roman dating and, moreover, probably did argue the case for it in Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] For many years, the people of Leinster made a triennial tribute payment, called the *Borumha*, to the Uí Néill.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Around 692, the King of Leinster was prepared to go to war over the payment, but first sent a delegation led by Saint Moling to ask for its remittance.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Fínsnechta Fledach agreed to remit payment "for a day and a night".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Moling argued that "All time is day and night; thou canst never reimpose this tax." Although this was not the king's intention, Moling held him to his word, promising him heaven if he kept it, and the reverse if he did not.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] When Adomnán learned of this he left Iona to see the king and scolded him soundly for yielding the rights of the Uí Néill.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It is generally believed that in 697, Adomnán promulgated the *Cáin Adomnáin*, meaning literally the "Canons" or "Law of Adomnán".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] The *Cáin Adomnáin* was promulgated amongst a gathering of Irish, Dál Riatan and Pictish notables at the Synod of Birr in 697.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] It is a set of laws designed, among other things, to guarantee the safety and immunity of various types of non-combatants in warfare.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] For this reason it is also known as the *Lex Innocentium* (Law of Innocents).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán's most important work, and the one for which he is best known, is the *Vita Columbae* ("Life of Columba"), a hagiography of Iona's founder, Columba, probably written between 697 and 700.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] The format borrows to some extent from Sulpicius Severus' *Life of Saint Martin of Tours*.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán adapted traditional forms of Christian biography to group stories about Columba thematically rather than chronologically, and present Columba as comparable to a hero in Gaelic mythology.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Wetherill suggests that one of the motivations for writing the *Vita* was to offer Columba as a model for the monks, and thereby improve Adomnán's standing as abbot.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] The biography is by far the most important surviving work written in early-medieval Scotland, and is a vital source for our knowledge of the Picts, as well as a great insight into the life of Iona and the early-medieval Gaelic monk.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] However, the *Vita* was not his only work.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán also wrote the treatise *De Locis Sanctis* (i.e.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] "On Holy Places"), an account of the great Christian holy places and centres of pilgrimage.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán got much of his information from a Frankish bishop called Arculf, who had personally visited the Egypt, Rome, Constantinople and the Holy Land, and visited Iona afterwards.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán gave a copy to the scholar-king Aldfrith of Northumbria (685–704).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Also attributed to him is a good deal of Gaelic poetry, including a celebration of the Pictish King Bridei's (671–93) victory over the Northumbrians at the Battle of Dun Nechtain (685).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Adomnán died in 704, and became a saint in Scottish and Irish tradition, as well as one of the most important figures in either Scottish or Irish history.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] His death and feast day are commemorated on 23 September.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Along with Columba, he is joint patron of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Raphoe, which encompasses the bulk of County Donegal in the north-west of Ireland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] The Cathedral of St Eunan and St Columba (popularly known as St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] Eunan's Cathedral), the Catholic cathedral in that diocese, is in Letterkenny.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] In 727 the relics of Adomnán were brought to Ireland to renew the *Cáin Adomnáin* and they were returned to Iona in 730.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/adomnan] In County Sligo, just to the south, he is venerated as the founder of Skreen Abbey, now the site of the Church of Ireland church of Skreen Parish.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The **Christianisation of Scotland** was the process by which Christianity spread in what is now Scotland, which took place principally between the fifth and tenth centuries.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Christianity was probably introduced to what is now Lowland Scotland by Roman soldiers stationed in the north of the province of Britannia.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] After the collapse of Roman authority in 410 AD, Christianity is presumed to have survived among the British enclaves in the south of what is now Scotland, but retreated as the pagan Anglo-Saxons advanced.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Traditional narratives depict Scotland as largely converted by Irish missions associated with figures such as St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Columba, from the fifth to the seventh centuries, but many of these figures were later constructs or founded monasteries and collegiate churches in areas to which Christianity had already spread.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] After the reconversion of Scandinavian Scotland in the tenth century, Christianity under papal authority was the dominant religion of the kingdom.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The process of Christianisation was also significant in the development of Scottish national identity, the Hiberno-Scottish mission to Continental Europe, the development of Insular art, and the introduction of Latin and formal education.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Very little is known about religion in Scotland before the arrival of Christianity.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The lack of native written sources among the Picts means that it can only be judged from parallels elsewhere, occasional surviving archaeological evidence and hostile accounts of later Christian writers.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] It is generally presumed to have resembled Celtic polytheism.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The names of more than two hundred Celtic deities have been noted, some of which, like Lugh, The Dagda and The Morrigan, come from later Irish mythology, whilst others, like Teutates, Taranis and Cernunnos, come from evidence from Gaul.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The Celtic pagans constructed temples and shrines to venerate these gods, something they did so through votive offerings and performing sacrifices, possibly including human sacrifice.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] According to Greek and Roman accounts, in Gaul, Britain and Ireland, there was a priestly caste of "magico-religious specialists" known as the druids, although very little is definitely known about them.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Irish legends about the origin of the Picts and stories from the life of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Ninian, associate the Picts with druids.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The Picts are also associated in Christian writing with "demon" worship, which may be a Christian interpretation of their deities, and one story concerning St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Columba has him exorcising a demon from a well in Pictland, suggesting that the worship of well spirits was a feature of Pictish paganism.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Roman mentions of the worship of the Goddess Minerva at wells, and a Pictish stone associated with a well near Dunvegan Castle on Skye, have been taken to support this case.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The roots of Christianity in Scotland were probably among the soldiers and ordinary Roman citizens who lived in the vicinity of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The archaeology of the Roman period indicates that the northern parts of the Roman province of Britannia were among the most Christianised in the island.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Chi-Rho inscriptions and Christian grave-slabs have been found on the wall from the fourth century, and from the same period the Mithraic shrines (known as Mithraea) that existed along Hadrian's Wall were attacked and destroyed, presumably by Christians.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] After the collapse of Roman authority in the early fifth century, four major circles of influence emerged in Northern Britain.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In the east, the kingdoms of the Picts eventually stretched from the River Forth to Shetland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In the west were the Gaelic (Goidelic)-speaking people of Dál Riata, who had close links with Ireland, from where they brought with them the name Scots.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In the south were the British (Brythonic-speaking) descendants of the peoples of the Roman-influenced kingdoms of "The Old North", the most powerful and longest surviving of which was Alt Clut.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Finally, the Anglo-Saxons had overrun much of southern Britain and held the Kingdom of Bernicia (later the northern part of Northumbria), which reached into what are now the Borders of Scotland in the south-east.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] While the Picts and Scots would have remained pagan, most scholars presume that Christianity would have survived after the departure of the Romans among the Brythonic enclaves and retreated as the Anglo-Saxons advanced north.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Their gods included Tiw, Woden, Thor and Frig, all of whom gave their names to days of the week, and Eostre, whose name was appropriated for the spring festival of Easter.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] While British Christians continued to practice inhumation without grave goods, the pagan Anglo-Saxons are visible in the archaeological record from their practice of cremation and burial in urns, accompanied by extensive grave goods, perhaps designed to accompany the dead to the afterlife.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] However, despite growing evidence of Anglian settlement in southern Scotland, only one such grave has been found, at Dalmeny in East Lothian.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The traditional view of the Christianisation of Scotland has seen it as carried out by Irish-Scots missionaries and to a lesser extent those from Rome and England.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Historian Richard Fletcher argued that motivations for these missions may have included the example of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Patrick, the idea of Peregrinatio and a growing interest in evangelism.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Missionaries from Ireland were operating on the British mainland from at least the sixth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] This movement is traditionally associated with the figures of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] However, historian Gilbert Markus highlights the fact that most of these figures were not church-founders, but were usually active in areas where Christianity had already become established, probably through gradual diffusion that is almost invisible in the historical record.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] This would have included trade, conquest and intermarriage.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Most scholars agree that the place-name element *eccles-*, from the Brythonic word for church, represents evidence of the British church of the Roman and immediate post-Roman period.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In Scotland most of these are located in the south of the country in the area of the British successor states that would be known as the Hen Ogledd, or the Old North.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] From the fifth and sixth centuries, inscribed stones indicate Christianity through their dedications and are spread across southern Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The earliest is the so-called Latinus stone of Whithorn, dating to around 450.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] A slightly later stone at Kirkmadrine commemorates *sacerdotes*, which may be bishops.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Among the key indicators of Christianisation are cemeteries containing long cists, which are generally east–west in orientation, like Christian graves.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] These cemeteries are suspected, or known to be Christian, because of their proximity to a church, or because they have Christian inscriptions.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] They are found from between the end of the Roman era in the early fifth century and the twelfth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] They are concentrated strongly in eastern Scotland south of the River Tay, in the modern East and Borders of Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Patrick also mentioned Coroticus, who probably ruled from the fort at Dumbarton rock and who had already accepted Christianity.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The poem *Y Gododdin*, set in the early sixth century and probably written in what is now Scotland, indicates that the warriors of Gododdin, probably a kingdom based the site of modern Edinburgh, were Christian, receiving communion and confessing their sins before battle.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Ninian, traditionally credited with introducing Christianity to the region of south-west Scotland, is now widely regarded as a later construct and may have been the result of scribal confusion with the Irish saint Finnian.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The church known as Candida Casa was dedicated to him at Whithorn in the sixth century and from there St Kentigern seems to have created a new centre of worship at Govan or Inchinnan, which would extend an influence across the Strathclyde region.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] However, it is clear that Christianity had already gained a foothold across what is now southern Scotland before the sixth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The conversion of the Gaelic kingdom of Dál Riata in the west of modern Scotland is traditionally attributed to the work of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In this view, the role of clergy owing their loyalty to Iona and elsewhere was to consolidate the position of Christianity in the region and beyond and to provide pastoral care for the people there.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] St Columba was probably a disciple of Finnian.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] He left Ireland after being exiled, and founded the monastery at Iona off the west coast of Scotland in 563, probably on land granted from a Christian king.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] From there missions were carried out to western Argyll and the islands around Mull.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Later the influence of Iona would extend to the Hebrides.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Iona emerged as the most important religious centre in the north of Britain, partly as a result of the work of Adomnan, who was abbot there from 679 to 704.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Although it is unclear whether the historic Columba did conduct missions outside of a small part of Dál Riata, Adoman's *Life of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Columba* elevated him to become the apostle of North Britain in general.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The means and speed by which the Picts converted to Christianity is uncertain.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Bede gives the credit for the conversion to Ninian, probably because in the eighth century, when Bede was writing, the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Northumbria was in control of the south-west of Scotland and an English bishop was in possession of the see that theoretically had been Ninian's.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Bede may have been reminding the Pictish church of its allegiance.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Adomnan stresses the role of Columba in Pictland, and although the saint may have visited the region, since Adomnan does not make any claims for conversion, it is unlikely that the saint had any major impact.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] A separate mission, that may have been an attempt to evangelise the north-east, was undertaken by Columba's younger contemporary, another Irish priest, Donnán of Eigg, who had a large number of churches dedicated in his name in the region.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The process of conversion may have begun earlier than traditional mission-based narratives.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] It is likely that knowledge of Christianity reached the region from Dál Riata, with which it had close contacts, including war, trade and intermarriage.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Traditions place the fifth-century saint Palladius in Pictland after he left Ireland, and link Abernethy with his contemporary, Saint Brigid of Kildare.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Evidence for an early date for Christianisation include the fact that St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Patrick, active in the fifth century, referred in a letter to "apostate Picts", indicating that they had previously been Christian, but had abandoned the faith.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In addition the poem *Y Gododdin* does not remark on the Picts as pagans.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Recent archaeological work at Portmahomack places the foundation of the monastery there, an area once assumed to be among the last converted, in the late sixth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In the east and north, Class II Pictish stones began to show Christian symbolism from the early eighth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Conversion of the Pictish élite is assessed to have taken place over a considerable period, beginning in the fifth century and not complete until the seventh.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Conversion of the general population may have stretched into the eighth century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The evidence of place names suggests a wide area of Ionan influence in Pictland, where there are large numbers of dedications of churches to Iona abbots of the seventh century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Aidan (died 651) went from Iona to found a church at Lindisfarne off the east coast of Northumbria.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The influence of Lindisfarne would spread through the kingdom of Northumbria into what is now south-east Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] However, in the second half of the century, the Northumbrian church was increasingly influenced by the Roman form of Christianity.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Wilfred (active from the 660s until his death in 709), abbot of the monastery at Ripon and Bishop of Northumbria, and Benedict Biscop (c.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] 628–690), founder of the monasteries of Jarrow and Wearmouth, intensified ties with Rome.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] A bishopric established at Abercorn in the region of West Lothian, is presumed to have adopted Roman forms of Christianity after the Synod of Whitby in 664, at which King Oswiu of Northumbria accepted the arguments for Roman authority and practices.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] However, the Pictish victory at the Battle of Dunnichen in 685 ended the Northumbrian dominance of the region and the bishop and his followers were ejected.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The result of different missions and forms of conversion was a series of overlapping and informally organised churches.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In the past historians used the term Celtic Church to describe a specific form of Christianity with its origins in the conversion of Ireland, traditionally associated with St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Patrick and which later spread to northern Britain through Iona.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] It is also used as a general description for the Christian establishment of northern Britain prior to the twelfth century, when new religious institutions and ideologies of primarily French origin began to take root in Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The Celtic form of Christianity has been contrasted with that derived from missions from Rome, which reached southern England in 587 under the leadership of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Subsequent missions from Canterbury then helped convert the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms, reaching Northumbria in the early eighth century, where Iona had already begun to have a presence.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] As a result, Christianity in Northumbria became a mix of Celtic and Roman influences.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] While Roman and Celtic Christianity were very similar in doctrine and both accepted ultimate papal authority, there were differences in practice.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The most contentious were the method of calculating Easter, and the form of head shaving for priests known as tonsure.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Other differences were in the rites of ordination and baptism, and in the form of service of the liturgy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In addition scholars have identified significant characteristics of the organisation of Irish and Scottish Christianity as relaxed ideas of clerical celibacy, intense secularisation of ecclesiastical institutions, and the lack of a diocesan structure.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] This made abbots (or *coarbs*), rather than bishops, the most important element the church hierarchy.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Wilfred was the major spokesman for the Roman case at the Synod of Whitby in 664, which was called by King Oswiu of Northumbria to decide which form of observance would be used in his kingdom, and where he decided in favour of the Roman form of tonsure and of calculating Easter.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Although this only affected Anglo-Saxon Northumbria, from this point the distinctiveness of Celtic Christianity declined.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Nechtan mac Der-Ilei, king of the Picts from 706, seems to have attempted to establish links with the church in Northumbria.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Before 714 he wrote to Ceolfrith, abbot of Wearmouth, asking for a formal refutation of the Irish position over the calculation of the date of Easter and for help in building a stone church "in the manner of the Romans".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Duncan has suggested that there was a "Romanising group" among Nechtan's clergy, perhaps led by Bishop Curitan, who took the name Latin name Boniface.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] This is also suggested by the presence of a church at Rosemarkie in Ross and Cromarty, dedicated to St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Peter, seen as the first Bishop of Rome, by the early eighth century, and subsequent similar dedications in Pictish territory.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] By the mid-eighth century, Iona and Ireland had accepted Roman practices.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Iona's place as the centre of Scottish Christianity was disrupted by the arrival of the Vikings, first as raiders, then as conquerors.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] In 806, 68 monks were killed and the next year the abbot withdrew to Kells in Ireland, taking the relics of St.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] There were periodic returns of abbots and relics, often ending in more massacres.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Orkney, Shetland, Western Isles and the Hebrides eventually fell to the pagan Norsemen, curtailing the influence of the church in the Highlands and Islands.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The threat posed by the Vikings may have forced a union between the kingdoms of Dál Riata and the Picts under Kenneth mac Alpin, traditionally dated to 843.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The abbot of the new monastery at Dunkeld emerged as the Bishop of the new combined Kingdom of Alba, which would subsequently come to be known as the Kingdom of Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] While the official conversion of Scandinavian Scotland took place at the end of the tenth century, there is evidence that Christianity had already made inroads into the Viking controlled Highland and Islands.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] There are a large number of isles called Pabbay or Papa in the Western and Northern Isles, which may indicate a "hermit's" or "priest's isle" from this period.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Changes in patterns of grave goods and Viking place names using -kirk also suggest that Christianity had begun to spread before the official conversion.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] According to the *Orkneyinga Saga*, not written down until around 1230, the Northern Isles were Christianised by Olav Tryggvasson, king of Norway, in 995 when he stopped at South Walls on his way from Ireland to Norway.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The King summoned the local *jarl* Sigurd the Stout and said "I order you and all your subjects to be baptised.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] If you refuse, I'll have you killed on the spot and I swear I will ravage every island with fire and steel".
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The story may be apocryphal, but the islands became officially Christian, receiving their own bishop in the early eleventh century.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The bishopric appears to have been under the authority of the Archbishops of York and of Hamburg-Bremen at different points before the twelfth century and from then until 1472 it was subordinate to the Archbishop of Nidaros (today's Trondheim).
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Elsewhere in Scandinavian Scotland the record is less clear.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] There was a Bishop of Iona until the late tenth century, followed by a gap of more than a century, possibly filled by the Bishops of Orkney, before the appointment of the first Bishop of Mann in 1079.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] One of the major effects of the conversion of the Vikings was to bring an end to plundering raids on Christian sites, which may have allowed them to recover some of their status as cultural and intellectual centres.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] It also probably curbed the excesses of Viking violence and led to a more settled society in northern Scotland.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The Christianisation of Scotland brought the country into the cultural mainstream of Europe.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] When the Kingdom of Alba emerged in the ninth century it would be an overtly Christian kingdom and, despite its cultural diversity, religion would be a major source of Scottish identity.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The Canmore dynasty that would rule Scotland from the eleventh century to the end of the thirteenth identified itself with Christianity and a strong relationship emerged between the crown and church.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Scottish monasticism also played a major part in the Hiberno-Scottish mission, by which Scottish and Irish clergy undertook missions to the expanding Frankish Empire.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] They founded monasteries, often called Schottenklöster (meaning *Gaelic monasteries* in German), most of which became Benedictine establishments in what is now Germany.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Cathróe of Metz, became local saints in the region.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] After the conversion of the Picts and the assimilation of Pictish culture into that of the Scots and Angles a common artistic style emerged in Britain and Ireland, known as Insular art.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Surviving examples are found in metalwork and carving, but mainly in illuminated manuscripts, highly decorated with intricate patterning, like the Book of Kells—which may have been wholly or partly created in Iona.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Insular art became highly influential in continental Europe, contributing to the development of Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] The establishment of Christianity brought Latin to Scotland as a scholarly and written language.
[src:christianisation-of-scotland/christianisation-of-scotland] Monasteries served as major repositories of knowledge and education, often running schools and providing a small educated elite, who were essential to create and read documents in a largely illiterate society.
